The Core 8  Clinical Features
Age: This is the most basic demographic factor and is a primary risk indicator in every medical dataset.

Lesion Shape: Describes the geometric outline of the mass (e.g., Round, Oval, Irregular).

Margin Type: Describes the border of the mass; "Spiculated" or "Indistinct" margins are high-risk indicators compared to "Circumscribed" ones.

Tissue Composition: The density/background of the breast tissue (e.g., Fatty, Fibroglandular, Dense), which affects how easily a mass can be seen.

Echogenicity: Refers to how the mass reflects ultrasound waves (e.g., Hypoechoic, Isoechoic). This is a standard metric in almost all ultrasound-based clinical data.

Posterior Acoustic Features: Describes what happens to the sound waves behind the mass (e.g., Shadowing or Enhancement). Shadowing is a classic sign often associated with malignancy.

Orientation (Parallel vs. Non-Parallel): Often called "taller-than-wide." A mass that grows vertically (non-parallel to the skin) is a significant warning sign in clinical assessments.

